			<title>Windows 8</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?74524-Windows-8&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Wed, 12 Dec 2012 20:37:17 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[No more Media Center, however, Music and Video apps (out of the box) covers the majority of that functionality, and is integrated with the Microsoft Store/Xbox Music service. Also, I still use WinAMP, so this doesn't matter a lot to me, I imagine a lot of you use VLC or something similar. Windows 8...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>No more Media Center, however, Music and Video apps (out of the box) covers the majority of that functionality, and is integrated with the Microsoft Store/Xbox Music service. Also, I still use WinAMP, so this doesn't matter a lot to me, I imagine a lot of you use VLC or something similar. Windows 8 comes with the ability to mount ISO files out of the box, no need for VCD or anything of the sort.<br />
<br />
Sandboxed app selection is pretty weak at this point, except on the Entertainment front, where you've got Netflix, Hulu+, and several major network apps that are all really nice. Games selection in the store seems mostly targeted at Windows 8 RT devices (phone, Surface, etc.).<br />
<br />
Getting used to running Desktop like any other App in the system took all of a day, the new Start Screen that replaces the start menu is way more functional in so many ways than the old start menu, but overall the entire UI is majorly overhauled, like the difference between Windows 3 and Windows 95 different. The various &quot;corner functions&quot; are pretty nice, right side top and bottom corners takes you to the &quot;quick control panel&quot; which has your search, settings, devices, sharing controls and a clickable link to the Start screen. Top left and bottom left provide the task swapping functions for Apps, that is, if you're running the Netflix app, the Skype app, the Desktop app and the Wikipedia app, you use these corner menus to manage the app tasks (tabbing Desktop apps still works as before).<br />
<br />
<img src="http://carryingthewhale.azurewebsites.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/apptabber.png" border="0" alt="" /><br />
<br />
For Microsoft-branded productivity, the new Office 2013 and associated suite of productivity tools are a little different from previous versions. The entire Windows platform has adapted to this concept of &quot;workflow&quot;, and pretty much all of the tools, if they don't actually use workflow, have been redesigned to use workflow concepts (Windows Workflow is an actual Windows programming component, used heavily in things like build tools, SharePoint, and several advanced apps like Dynamics). This includes the Office 2013 suite, which now starts you on a Start screen in each app, rather than defaulting to a blank document, for example.<br />
<br />
The idea being here that when you're working through your process, you're going to start by thinking, &quot;I need to do X and the tool to do that is Word,&quot; so therefore you open Word, but you might not always want to start a new document, perhaps you want to open an old one. The Start page in each app allows you to start your personal workflow with the app, and then you decide what you're going to do next, open an old doc, start a new one, publish an existing doc to the Cloud, and a few other things. The idea being that the app makes fewer decisions for you and instead facilitates your workflow.<br />
<br />
Explorer and finally Visio and Project have been updated with the Ribbon bar, some additional functionality has been added to Explorer and all of the Office apps in the top right corner you now have a button next to Minimize, Maximize, Close that allows you to control the state of the ribbon bar, either auto-hide, hidden, or shown. Explorer and the entire suite of system monitoring tools have been completely revamped, and they're actually bad ass awesome now. Task manager provides a whole lot more useful info now, like overall CPU consumption by apps, memory consumption, by app, over time usage by app or service, and really nice charts and tables showing you how your system is performing. The really sweet tweak is to the File Copy dialog, though, which now gives you a progress bar that is also a chart showing bitrate history during the copy.<br />
<br />
<img src="http://carryingthewhale.azurewebsites.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/copystatus.png" border="0" alt="" /><br />
<br />
Overall, I'm very pleased with Windows 6.2. I would still recommend waiting for SP1 for Office 2013/Windows 8, but the number of problems with the RTM release compared to most is really clean overall.<br />
<br />
EDIT: Also, one final note, one click reimage is EPIC.<br />
<br />
<img src="http://carryingthewhale.azurewebsites.net/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/refresh.png" border="0" alt="" /></div>

]]></content:encoded>
